</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=suladasbardspeed>Suladas Bardspeed</A> at: 6/5/04 10:28 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raiddinn>Raiddinn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Minstrel</span><br>  Posts: 238<br> <font color=#330000>(6/6/04 5:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19464.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ~</span><hr size=1> DKP bidding sucks, I have never heard of it being applied successfully at the highest level, some examples of where it falls short are:<br>
1) There are 5 monks in guild, you are raiding an area that just happens to drop monk only items that they all want, the 5 monks get together before the raid, all 5 random 100, highest winner bids 1 and all others dont bid that raid.  Phenominal weapon, phenominal upgrade for all goes for the absolute lowest value.<br>
<br>
This absolutely must be moderated, this cannot happen, this is the stupidest thing about DKP bidding and will destroy the whole system.<br>
<br>
2) Officer corruption, this applies mostly to single bid /tell systems.  People /tell the loot caller 5 10 20 or whatever, officer tells his friend the max bid, friend bids max + 1, grats.<br>
<br>
Again, this must be moderated, but it cannot be with the exception of real time logs, which can most likely not work in practice.<br>
<br>
Open bidding with anyone able to view the bidding really exposes problem #1 for what it is, but with no reason to change it, the classes that it relates to will continue to abuse it.  About the only way to stop problem 2 are having people /tell 1 random officer their bid (of course officers friends will /tell the officer thats their friend here) and then officers random for who says the order of their bids, at least then the officer would have a chance at making his friend win only 1 time per however many officers there are on average.<br>
<br>
Really, DKP bidding is seriously flawed, item costs must be in relation to equivalent items, with class specific items being priced slightly less than the equivalent item for another class.  <br>
<br>
This must also be in relation to items for the same class.  If a bard only weapon item gives a 20% DPS upgrade then it should go for about 2/3 of the price that an all/all weapon would that would give the average warrior/ranger/whatever a 20% dps upgrade, if, due to double attack not being a factor a beastlord or bard weapon would give less DPS to that class than it would for a dual wielder they should have to pay less for that weapon.<br>
<br>
I was a guild leader for a long while in a fairly worthless guild by todays standards, but I had a good DKP system set up and to this day I dont really know anyone that disliked it that used it.<br>
<br>
We had fixed prices for each item, all relative to each other, officer council decided prices on items and once it was decided once it was always that price, DKP spent then gets divided to everyone present at the raid afterwards. <br>
<br>
People bid (put their name in the virtual hat saying they want it) and whoever bids with the most points wins.  Going negative is 100% ok as far as you want to go but as long as you are fighting mobs that give the majority of the guild upgrades then people can rarely win items with less than 0 points anyway so its not often an issue.  Recruits will often go very negative on stuff that the guild is backflagging/backfarming on if they are weaker geared than the rest of the guild, but thats ok too.  <br>
<br>
The DKP prices of items would go up over time, say just 1dkp per 2 hp on the item and you would end with 15 points for 30hp items, 30 points for 60hp items, 50 points for 100hp items, 60 for 120hp, etc and you can see the costs increasing as the expansions go by, that is to be expected, again thats just a base *guess* price, modified by item effects etc also.<br>
<br>
If nobody loots the items then nobody gets points and we usually just quit doing the encounter since no bidding on items that drop from it would give that indication.<br>
<br>
There was a few of us with VT items that split off to make the guild and we were very well geared compared to the rest of the guild to start with and we had lots of point hoarding between us, purely because we for the most part had nothing ever drop that would upgrade us, I personally never saw an upgrade and had 100% raid attendance and 100% raid dkp at the end of the guild, but the other 2 got to spend some of theirs on well deserved items as well when they were available.<br>
<br>
My current loot council guild works well enough, but those types can be corrupted beyond belief just at the outset and everyone expects that when they agree to it so thats ok too I guess.  In the ideal world loot council is the best kind to use, but the real world is often very far from ideal.<br>
<br>
Impressario Raiddinn the Beatdropper<br>
